 has done tests....<br>
<br>
A cleric in my guild, mikar, has been doing a few tests based off some things that have been posted on other boards. What he has been showing is that spells cast in his specialization are getting a 10 to 12 percent cut in mana on EVERY cast but he is never getting more or less than that. IE, specialization = 10 or so percent reduction on all spells cast once skill is high enough.Thats the summary, here is a paste of his tests... anyone gotten similar results or have a larger test pool? The reason I am wondering about this, I have seen spells cast for what seems like only a tic or two of mana when its a 400mana spell. But I have never been able to officially test or know as we dont know our exact mana numbers and I could of just been wrong guessing where my mana was at.<br>
<br>
&quot;&quot;Patch time - so allow me to pick your brains for ideas about this.<br>
<br>
The description of Specialization on Castersrealm (for what its worth) says:<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
How does it work?<br>
<br>
When a spell is cast a roll is thrown to see if it receives the specialisation bonus. The higher your specialisation skill the more likely it is the roll will succeed, and the greater the benefit of the roll. A successful roll will do two things: <br>
<br>
It will reduce the mana used on the spell. <br>
It will reduce the chance of fizzling. <br>
An unsuccessful roll will merely cause you to cast the spell with normal mana cost and fizzle chance.<br>
<br>
Note: It has been confirmed by Geoffrey Zatkin, the once Arch-Magi at Verant that: <br>
<br>
Specialisation does not increase chance of recovering after interruption. This is based purely on Channelling <br>
Specialisation does not make spells cast faster. This is a fixed amount. <br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok - chance to reduce mana used and risk of fizzling. Fizzling is near impossible to test I think - as you would need an extremely long log so for the moment I will forget about that and focus on the &quot;chance to reduce mana cost&quot;.<br>
<br>
As a base I logged on my level 16 magician with no specialization yet. Standing with no buffs I cast a 160 mana cost spell the very tick it was possible and then counted number of ticks before I could cast it again. Expected result 160 ticks. Did this 3 times and got 157, 158 and 159 ticks. A small sample I admit but it gives an indication of the margin of error.<br>
<br>
I then logged Mikar on and cast a 100 mana cost spell in my main spec with 2 mana/tick due to MC1. Results from 10 tries were half 44 and half 45 ticks. I have also done a few other tries with higher cost spells and gotten the same 10-12% decrease in mana cost. Not once have I gotten something else though.<br>
<br>
Finally, I just cast a 150 mana non main spec spell twice (before patch cut me short) with 3 mana per tick due to MC2. Results were 48 and 49 ticks.<br>
<br>
I readily admit that my testing is still far from extensive enough to make any real conclusions but sofar it seems that the mana reduction from 200 spec *isnt* a chance but rather a steady 10% reduction thats added to a small inherent reduction in the size of a few percent. <br>
<br>
A hypothesis of mine is that once your spec is either 100+ or 200+ the chance of spec to work is 100% giving a 10% reduction - with a chance below 100% with 50 spec giving a 10% reduction when it fires (this is in conflict with the description from Castersrealm, I know). I obviously need a 10% reduction from a non main spec spell a few times to make this a plausible explanation as well as a larger sample of main spec casts.<br>
<br>
Anyway - any comments, ideas, references to other tests or indeed any help with testing this - would be most welcome. <br>
Mikar of the Nexus<br>
High Priest of Brell<br>
The Companions<br>
The Tribunal <br>
